    "body": "Same problem for me. I'm on a DSL connection in Miami, and although I initially connect to around 200-2000 peers, it stalls some time between a few minutes to an hour later, and I'm sitting mining the same block that never changes. I've tried things like --maxpeers \"32\" and --maxpendpeers \"1\", but these options don't seem to be respected in any regard.\n\nEdit: \nAfter specifying(or not) --nat \"extip:local.subnet.address.here\" or --nat \"extip:my.public.address.here\", the socket appears to be listening on 0.0.0.0.\n\nEdit 2:\nTurns out it was properly listening on the \"any\" interface, but a rule on my router was tripped and subsequently dropping the insanely large amount of connections. Is there any way to make it not go completely crazy and flood my connection upon initialization?\n\nEdit 3:\nAfter dropping this rule, things are working a little better, but this is in no way a solution. After an hour, I still only get 1 outbound connection, with ~50-150 inbound.\n\nEdit 4:\nNope. 700 seconds on the same block when the chain is clearly moving on etherchain.org. This is with 1 outbound connection and ~200 inbound.\n",
